BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Website-cover-images-new-18.png
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260513T094205Z
DESCRIPTION:Join us for a guided walk of Beneath the Turning Sky\, led by Priya Chauhan\, one of the curators from the MAP Exhibitions team. This session explores key works from the exhibition\, unpacking the artistic practices\, material approaches\, and ideas that shape its narratives around ecology\, climate\, and our relationship with the natural world.\nThrough close looking and thoughtful discussion\, this session reveals the stories behind the artworks\, how they were made\, why they matter\, and the questions they pose about our place in the universe. It’s an invitation to slow down\, observe closely\, and discover new layers of meaning within the exhibition.\nThis event is part of International Museum Day programming.
DTEND:20260524T113000Z
DTSTART:20260524T103000Z
SUMMARY:Beneath the Turning Sky
UID:1277@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/beneath-the-turning-sky-5/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-2026-04-10T161153.475.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260429T065159Z
DESCRIPTION:Image credit: M. Palani Kumar\nA portfolio review session led by photographer and journalist M. Palani Kumar\, founder of the People’s Photographers Archive\, whose work documents the lives of working-class women and marginalized communities. The session offers an opportunity to explore how personal stories can be situated within broader societal narratives through visual practice\, while engaging with the idea of “witness” in long-term documentary work. Drawing on projects spanning 8–9 years\, it reflects on themes of caste violence\, forced evictions\, and environmental degradation\, examining their impact on both ecology and the communities that depend on it. \n\nParticipants are invited to present portfolios that engage with caste- and lineage-based narratives as lived experiences\, and to consider how to document working-class lives\, gender\, and labour with sensitivity and accountability. Emphasizing ethical representation and storytelling from within communities\, the session foregrounds the importance of centering and amplifying voices that are often marginalized or unheard. \n\nPlease submit your portfolio on the form by May 10\, 2026 9pm IST. \n\nThis event is part of programming around Beneath the Turning Sky in collaboration with People's Archives of Rural India (PARI)
DTEND:20260516T110000Z
DTSTART:20260516T080000Z
SUMMARY:Image as Witness: Portfolio Review with Palani Kumar
UID:1262@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/image-as-witness-portfolio-review-with-palani-kumar-2/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Vishal_Kumaraswamy_Marana_02.jpg
CATEGORIES:Talks,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260513T074859Z
DESCRIPTION:Image credits: Vishal Kumaraswamy/Marana\nWe hear from Vishal Kumaraswamy\, an artist-curator about his practices and projects. Stemming from anti-caste working principles\, his practice brings together traditional and experimental forms to investigate the entanglements of body\, caste\, language\, technology\, and society. He is interested in the power and potential of media technologies to imagine embodied\, gestural ways of fostering the further development of Dalit cultural practices.\n\nCentral to their inquiry is the continuity of Dalit ritualistic and cultural practices\, Marana (on funeral processions) and how these embodied performances are impacted by shifting urban spaces and technological intervention. Kumaraswamy investigates how technology can be repurposed to document and sustain these legacies rather than erase them. He creates space for new\, collaborative modes of representation that challenge dominant urban narratives.\n\nAfter the talk\, Kumaraswamy discusses with Aarti Sunder\, an artist whose interests lie within techno-politics\, focusing on the study of infrastructure – contemporary labour practices\, fiction\, myth\, digital-terrestrial play to expanded platform politics.\n\nThe event is presented as part of a monthly series that brings in artists and artistic practices rooted in Bengaluru\, developed in collaboration with Ananya Drishya.
DTEND:20260515T133000Z
DTSTART:20260515T123000Z
SUMMARY:Towards a New Commons: Technology\, Media and Dalit Cultural Practices
UID:1271@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/towards-a-new-commons-technology-media-and-dalit-cultural-practices/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Untitled-design-3.png
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260513T094359Z
DESCRIPTION:Join us for a guided walk of the exhibition Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany\, and Empire by Breanne Coelho from the MAP Team.\nBetween the 17th and 20th centuries\, the Indian subcontinent was the site of extensive botanical surveys under colonial rule. Plant collection and classification were closely tied to imperial economic\, medical\, and political interests\, and botanical illustration played a central role in this project. \nBringing together a new and historically significant collection of botanical art from this period\, the exhibition draws on recent scholarship to recover the often uncredited identities and histories of the Indian artists who made them.
DTEND:20260531T111500Z
DTSTART:20260531T103000Z
SUMMARY:Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany and Empire
UID:1279@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/paper-gardens-art-botany-and-empire/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-2026-04-02T112617.763.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260408T045758Z
DESCRIPTION:Five days\, a museum full of inspiration\, and a workshop unlike any other\, join film maker Hansa Thapliyal for doll-making and stop-motion animation at MAP.\n\nUsing the museum as a creative playground\, participants will work with everyday materials and scraps to build their own dolls\, drawing inspiration from our exhibition Beneath the Turning Sky. Along the way\, they'll explore their ideas\, experiment with storytelling\, and find their own creative voice.\n\nThrough playful stop-motion exercises\, these ideas will begin to move\, building into a collaborative animated film screened at the end of Summer at MAP.\n\nParticipants are required to bring:\n\n-A mobile phone with a camera\n\n-A few discarded items from home to add a personal touch to the creations\n\nNote: \n\n-Please pack a lunch\, snacks\, and a water bottle for your child each day.\n\n-Every registered participant receives a gift store voucher of equal value\, redeemable at the MAP Gift Store. \n\n-If you're a working parent\, our café space is open for you to use while your child is in session.\n\nThese workshops are for children between the ages of 13-16 If you are between the ages of 8-12 check out our programme here.\n\nSpots are limited. Register early to secure your place.
DTEND:20260516T103000Z
DTSTART:20260511T043000Z
SUMMARY:Summer at MAP (Ages 13-16)
UID:1240@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/summer-at-map-ages-13-16/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Website-cover-images-new-1.png
CATEGORIES:Talks,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260507T054349Z
DESCRIPTION:Join us for a photo talk that journeys through the lives of nomadic pastoral communities whose movement\, labour\, and knowledge have long shaped the ecologies of the Indian subcontinent – across mountains\, deserts\, forests and more. Presented as part of the public programming for Beneath the Turning Sky\, and in collaboration with People’s Archive of Rural India (PARI)\, this session reflects on pastoralism as both livelihood and way of life—deeply attuned to seasons\, landscapes\, and the needs of livestock. .\n\nThrough photographs and conversation\, the talk will trace the lives of the Changpas of Ladakh and the Fakirani Jats of Kachchh—communities navigating fragile ecosystems while facing mounting pressures from climate change\, industrial expansion\, and displacement. Bringing together image-making and oral histories\, the session invites audiences to consider migration\, resilience\, and the futures of communities whose histories are often overlooked. \n\nThis event is part of programming around Beneath the Turning Sky in collaboration with People’s Archives of Rural India (PARI)
DTEND:20260516T130000Z
DTSTART:20260516T120000Z
SUMMARY:Photo Talk: Land\, Livelihood\, and Loss
UID:1264@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/photo-talk-land-livelihood-and-loss/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/IMG_7250-scaled.jpg
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260514T084917Z
DESCRIPTION:Go behind the scenes with MAP's conservation team to explore textile preservation in museums. This hands-on workshop covers museum storage and methods\, plus practical tips for safeguarding your cherished textile heirlooms at home.\nAfterward\, join our International Museum Day open house at the conservation lab.\nPlease note that this workshop has limited seats. Registrations are first-come\, first-served.
DTEND:20260524T073000Z
DTSTART:20260524T053000Z
SUMMARY:Caring for Textile Collections
UID:1276@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/caring-for-textile-collections/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Copy-of-DSC05127-scaled.jpg
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260513T100912Z
DESCRIPTION:Dive deeper into our collection with a guided walk of our visual storage by Tanya Maheshwari from the MAP Collections team\, and witness the sheer volume of art and artefacts carefully preserved.\n\nIn this session\, visitors will also understand the challenges of storage\, the importance of conservation\, and the surprising discoveries that await within our hidden spaces in the museum.
DTEND:20260524T113000Z
DTSTART:20260524T110000Z
SUMMARY:Visual Storage
UID:1280@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/visual-storage/
